english:
  title: Master Yin
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    It is said among the people that scholars devoted to classical learning are deficient in literary composition, while those devoted to literary composition are ignorant of classical learning. Yet from my observation, this is not so. Literary composition springs forth from classical learning—classical learning is the very root and foundation of literary composition. Consider the analogy of grass and trees: how could there be luxuriant branches and blossoms of rare beauty without roots and soil beneath? The Book of Poetry, the Book of History, and the Six Arts are all classical learning; the texts of these works constitute their literary expression. If one can penetrate their meaning through their words, examine them with precision, and steep oneself in their depths until principle and expression merge and flow together within one's breast, then when such a person speaks or composes, excellence arises unbidden and naturally. From ancient times, those whose literary works have resonated through their age and been transmitted to posterity have all followed this path.

    Yet people see today's so-called classical learning as merely the tedious parsing of phrases and exegetical commentary. They see today's so-called literary composition as merely clever ornamentation and intricate construction. How can mere phrase-parsing address the profound patterns of civilization and governance? How can mere ornamentation engage with the learning of human nature, principle, and virtue? Thus have men come to divide classical learning and literary composition into two separate pursuits, doubting they could ever serve one another. Alas, how shallow such views are!

    In this present age, should there arise one who stirs with vigor, rises above common custom, seeks upward into the deep mysteries of Confucius and Mencius, and moves freely within the realm of the creative—can we say no such person exists? If none exists, so be it. But if such a one does exist, would not the common people's division of learning and writing amount to deceiving the worthies of an entire generation?

    Such a person, I say, is Master Yin of Xiangyang, who held office under the throne. The Master possessed a nature both pure and steadfast; his learning was comprehensive and thorough. In the subtleties of principle and righteousness, he attained much through his own insight. Thus he rose to prominence in his native region and came to serve at court. For more than twenty years he held position at the National Academy, guiding and inspiring disciples without weariness even in old age. All the eminent officials and renowned scholars of his time emerged from his school. After Yang-cun, he alone exemplified the dignity of the teacher's way.

    Though literary composition was not his primary calling, his writings possess an elegant simplicity and apt directness. At first glance they appear plain, yet upon careful perusal they reveal abundant subtle flavor—all flowing from the Six Classics themselves. Among his contemporaries, such figures as Vice Director Kim Mal and Minister of Rites Kim Pan and Literary Scholar Kim Gou achieved comparable skill in classical learning, yet none could rival him in literary composition. Truly, Master Yin possessed virtues and talents of surpassing measure.

    Though his lifetime output was considerable, he would compose and then cast aside, leaving scarcely a page behind. His son, Ki-eun, who served as magistrate of Gunwi and was my fellow examination candidate, has painstakingly gathered what remained of these scattered fragments, collecting several pieces into a single volume. He has asked me to write a preface.

    I say this: Though the Master has long departed from the world, our people still regard him as one would regard Mount Tai or the Northern Stars. The precise and pure teachings he transmitted orally to his disciples—from officials and scholars down to common learners—all have been recorded in writing and passed down in praise. The great historians have inscribed his deeds in their records more than once. His accomplishments shine so brightly they will surely illuminate ages to come. What matter if these fragments and broken passages never spread widely? Yet consider: when a parent leaves behind even a hat or a shoe, a filial son carefully preserves and protects it. How much more should one treasure poems and writings that spring from a parent's very heart and take form through a parent's own voice? It is fitting that you, with devoted care, gather and preserve these works as an eternal legacy to your descendants. I too am one who has learned indirectly from the Master. How could I refuse to set brush to paper in this cause?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Master Yin refers to Yin Heon (尹愔), a renowned Confucian scholar and administrator of fifteenth-century Korea who served as an official in Xiangyang and later as an instructor at the National Academy (Taekhak). He was celebrated for both his classical learning and moral authority.
  - key: ''
    value: The Six Arts (六藝) traditionally comprise ritual, music, archery, charioteering, calligraphy, and mathematics—the core curriculum of classical Confucian education.
  - key: ''
    value: Yang-cun (陽村) refers to Yi Saek (李穡, 1328-1396), a earlier Korean Confucian master renowned for his teaching authority.
  - key: ''
    value: The allusion to 'Mount Tai or the Northern Stars' (泰山壯斗) evokes images of permanence and guidance, expressing how the Master's influence endures in the hearts of later generations.
